River_Gradient: Relatively steep gradient (e.g., mountainous or hilly terrain)
Canopy_Cover: No or almost no direct sunlight (>80% canopy cover)
Additional_Sampling_Notes:
-Just below US site. the stream drops subsurface for ~8m. It appears to be due to an intact collapsed bank (that is not soggy nor does it have surface water) but could be through another subsurface channel. Upstream of sites are an old earthenwork dam that has since filled in with a meadow. 
-The DS site is small - ~0.3m2
- Summer storms are highly infrequent at this site. but there was a thunderstorm about 3-4 days before sampling.

The field notes contain the following errors. which are corrected in this form:
- the written notes list the U-M distance as 5m (should be 10m). and D-M distance as 10m (should be 5m).
- access to sunlight: D and M have no shade (0% shading and 100% sunlight. instead of 100% canopy cover). The upstream site (U) has about 50% shading. 
Pictures: given the turbidity of the water. no pictures of the sediment could be taken. Sediments were collected by diving down into the water and scooping up sediment. The pictures uploaded represent the setting on land. not in the river. Sediment samples at D and M were fairly muddy. several sediment scoops at the upstream site contained a fair amount of leaves that were removed. 
Filter: the filter clogged after running the second set of replicates and at that point. we switched to the second filter (keeping the first filter clean). Filtering became difficult quickly again and filling vial ICR3 was challenging. When collecting samples for the third replicate for cations (CAT3). the sample collapsed (air might have gotten into the filter?) and water passed through the filter much more easily. We continued sampling CAT3. but the sample is much darker in color. indicating that the filter didn't work. and I suggest to discard that sample. We continued to filter the 125mL vial at the very end (S19S_0011_MER). After a little while. the filtering became harder again. so we discarded the water in it. filtered some more (~10mL). rinsed the bottle with that water and discarded it. and then filtered the required ~125mL. Thus. that sample *may* be valid. Given the above issues with filter #2. we preserved the first filter for microbial analyses with RNALater.

For the third 4-mL zero head space sample. the bottom of the glass vial cracked and fell off when screwing the lid onto the vial.  The sample was lost.

We were able to use one filter for most of the filtered water samples and had to change filters after filtering ~30 mL sample into the 125 mL PETG bottle.  It was not possible to filter an additional 700 mL through that filter.

The data entered on this online form are correct. I also had both filters clog by the time I completed the filtered water samples. and I was unable to collect the final filtered 125mL sample. Only the first filter is being returned. because there wasn't enough RNAlater to preserve the second. The river is multi-channel at the sampling site but generally is single channel. straight beyond the site.

Site_Name: US DOE Biological and Environmental Research (BER) Scientific Focus Area (SFA) watershed testbed site
Canopy_Cover: No or almost no direct sunlight (>80% canopy cover)
Additional_Sampling_Notes: Filter 1 (labelled as such) clogged after 2nd blue cap falcon tube.  After that: changed to Filter 2 (labelled as such).  Both filters preserved with RNAlater and sent to WHONDRS.  Filter 1 likely clogged because sediment was still disturbed after marking the locations when we began to collect samples.  Temperature and DO were measured two days prior to sampling. --- Very shallow. small stream; sampling site is at an intermittent stretch. located between perennially flowing stretches.  Usually dry during the summer. but water was running on Aug 29 follow rains the previous week. --- Pressure transducer data still being processed.  We will send it as soon as it is ready. in the next week.  --- Will also email info about nearest weather station once it is determined.

General_Vegetation: Broadleaf evergreen tree. Broadleaf deciduous tree
Additional_Sampling_Notes: For access reasons we sampled 3 km from the USGS gauging station. I have extensive experience working in the upper 20 km of the Lower Colorado downstream from Longhorn Dam. and can confirm that the conditions at our sampling site are representative of the river conditions near the USGS gauge. There are no major inflows between the sampling site and the USGS gauge so river conditions at the gauge are also representative of conditions at the sampling site.

Site_Name: NSF Long Term Ecological Research (LTER) site: Kellogg Biological Station
Additional_Sampling_Notes: Site is over 4km north/upstream of USGS gauging station with only one tributary (Ransom Creek) in between.  Discharge correction factor of 0.89 used to remove mean tributary discharge contribution.  i.e. USGS discharge of Augusta Creek on 12 Aug 2019 = 33 ft3/s = 0.93 m3/s.  Corrected for Ransom Creek. discharge at C Avenue site = 0.83 m3/s

Additional_Sampling_Notes: My assistant accidentally opened the non-acidified amber vial for 2 seconds. She did not touch the septum. We proceeded to fill the vial and send it with the other samples. We were able to fill all replicate samples and were still able to push another 720 ml of water through the filter. We could have pushed another 60-120 ml through (maybe moreWHON). I hope we captured enough microbial biomass. Our downstream site was below the USGS gage. while the mid and upstream sites were above the USGS gage.

Additional_Sampling_Notes: During sampling (10:30 to 13:00. British Summer Time) a small shower happened. ---  It was not possible to flush a single additional syringe volume through the filter after all samples have been collected (step 34 of the protocol); it was already extremely difficult to fill the last bottle (125ml plastic bottle; step 33) with the same filter; I therefore. in addition. used the second filter afterwards and flushed 4 syringe volumes through it (more were not possible); however. I haven't had more RNALater and therefore could not fill the filter with RNALater afterwards. --- the longitude values on the data sheet are given in degrees WEST (and are therefore positive); the values in this form. however. are given in degrees EAST (and are therefore negative). --- the parcel was packed on Aug 20th between 11am and 12 pm

Sediment_Collection_Depth_cm: 1-3 cm as described in the protocol
MiniDot_Notes: river stage/flow is visibly higher than initial visit. Visible white bubbles on surface flow. Weather is similar to the initial visit (80s and sunny, light wind).
Additional_Sampling_Notes: Sediment substrate surface very rich in dark green algae, with sandy textured material below algal/organic rich layer. Reach where sampling took place is effectively a partially natural flood conveyance channel: shallow sediment overlying concrete, pervasive rubbly material (cobble to boulder sized) placed across stream (see photos). Stream banks are natural sediment (as in CM_008-exposed photo) but inset within a large levee made of rip-rap and concrete. Upstream of site (~800m at Hellman Rd crossing), the stream is a flood conveyance channel lined 100% with concrete. Additionally, looks like some flow is siphoned off immediately upstream of sampling site (just below Hellman Rd crossing) to Mill Creek Wetlands as a form of stormwater/irrigation runoff treatment.
Hydrograph_Online: https://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?site_no=11073495  [USGS gauge located a few kilometers upstream of site, but likely representative]

Additional_Sampling_Notes: Water was slightly turbid (65.3 NTU), our ProDSS measured 109.7 % sat and 9.10 mg/L DO at start of minidot deployment. Specific Conductivity was 412.2 uS/cm. The filtered water bottle had ~100mL of unfiltered water in it, we went through all the filters.  The sieving was taking too long, so we started to pick out the large bits by hand (mostly snail shells).  Not all the photos fit, here's a link for more: https://www.dropbox.com/sh/386901lt9ci5plt/AAD9jwSM-Lycc65zSz11YRLAa?dl=0. We have 47 years of data from this location- nutrients and TSS.  There's a sonde deployed as well, if you need any diel DO or other details.

MiniDot_Notes: Vessel wake (see below) moved the sensor from rock so I had to secure it in place using a peg inserted through its hole and inserted deep in the river sediment. The sensor was maintained at a 50% depth of 10 cm (total water column depth 20 cm).
Additional_Sampling_Notes: Vessel wake was frequent and inevitable. I waited for water settling before sampling/resuming sampling (5 min). Not much resuspension.

Hydrograph_Online: https://waterdata.usgs.gov/monitoring-location/14171600/#parameterCode=00065&period=P7D  This gauge is downriver of the site and downstream of the confluence with the Mary's River

Sediment_Collection_Depth_cm: 1-3 cm as described in the protocol
MiniDot_Notes: Sensor held in place with a stick stuck in the  sediment.  Sensor positioned closer to the main channel than the sediment sampling, which was about a half meter closer to the bank.
Additional_Sampling_Notes: The second sediment RNAlater tube leaked during shipping and only contained 15 ml of RNAlater.  We added 0.2micron filter sterilized homemade RNAlater up to a total of 30ml prior to sampling. Sediments included a lot of organic materials that were served out including sticks, leaves, and some evergreen needles. Sampling site was in Avery Park in Corvallis, OR. River flow was very slow. Sampling site was at the downriver end of a gravel bar positioned on an inside bend in the river. There were overhanging deciduous trees.
Hydrograph_Online: https://waterdata.usgs.gov/monitoring-location/14171000/ this site is some distance upriver from the sampling site.

Organization: Idaho State University; University of Georgia
Weather: Very cloudy and slightly riany during sampling
Sediment_Collection_Depth_cm: 1-3 cm as described in the protocol
MiniDot_Notes: This DO sensor is deployed at the downstream of  USGS gauging station 02203603.
Additional_Sampling_Notes: 1. The labeled filter was broken when we filtered the first nutrient sample, so that we added RNA Later immediately to preserve it. However, we changed the new filter and it was broken again when we collected the second nutrient sample. Due to all of the needled filters broken, we failed to collect the third nutrient sample. 2. The 500 mL sediment cap is lost, I used a clean cap from my lab instead. 3. The second RNA sediment tube leaked solution in the ziploc, only 20mL solution was left in it. We collect third one from the extra supplies and it was labeled as CM_24_MIC_3.

Depositional_Type: Hard to say, river was so slow flowing
Additional_Sampling_Notes: River was pretty flat with steep incised banks near access point except a few feet away from a boat ramp structure, which is where I sampled. I was in ankle deep mud. (some large rodent like nutria)

Weather: Sunny, Cool (38 F air temp) slight breeze
General_Vegetation: Needleleaf evergreen tree, Broadleaf deciduous tree
MiniDot_Notes: USGS station 01073319 is located about 8 river km downstream and the URL is provided below. The North Branch River is enters the Lamprey River downstream of sampling site CM_062 and upstream of USGS station thus flow from USGS station 01073319 should be area weighted if used at collection site.
Additional_Sampling_Notes: We sampled upstream from the original site 18 on google maps at the Cotton Rd. crossing.  The original site 18 was not on a stream channel in google maps and was not directly accessible from the road.  We have long-term data at the CM_062 site sampled (our site LMP19). Tried using sieve for sediment collection, but not very effective.  Did not sieve most of the sample, but did pick out plant material and sediment >2 mm.

Sediment_Collection_Depth_cm: 1-3 cm as described in the protocol
MiniDot_Notes: Sensor was 1 m from "depositional bank" ( = sand, gravel over bedrock that has a stagnant, shallow water pool between it and the "real" bank of the river.). The sensor was about 5 m from the "real" bank at that point in time. We took water samples within 10 m down the river from the sensor because the river sediment was so fine that sampling disturbed sediment so that it may have interfered with the sensor readings.
Additional_Sampling_Notes: - Samples packed in ice 5:00 - 5:15  pm on 1/17/23 and driven to FedEx with a 5:45 pm pick up for overnight packages. Expected delivery at PNNL before 4 pm on 1/18/23. Tracking info: https://www.fedex.com/fedextrack/?trknbr=817383356941&trkqual=2459962000~817383356941~FX. Site weather = Sunny, 22C. I provided a diagram (sketch) of the site with estimated distances in the uploaded files section in this form.The bank was level with fine and course sediments - if vegetation was present it was grasses on the bank (grasses appeared to be some Phragmites sp. and/or Paspalum denticulatum). There was a steep incline up to a terrace (but it was not more than 4 m long) and the terrace was vegetated with hardwoods (dominated by Platanus occidentalis). Most importantly, there was a dry, ephemeral tributary at the "real" bank (see sensor notes above)nearest to area we sampled. There was evidence of erosional deposition present. The source of the ravine/tributary was a bare/muddy watering area of a densely populated cattle ranch. The river sediment was so fine that getting it through the filters was incredibly difficult (especially when using a 50 ml syringe) and therefore we used many filters. It would have been easier to use smaller syringes, but trying to fill a 500 ml bottle with a small syringe would have been tedious). Therefore the "filtered water" sample (BWT - filtered) had to be filled with non-filtered water. We managed to fill it to nearly 150 ml of filtered water, but it took 30 mins and we couldn't do that 3-4 more times. Therefore, we filled the remaining 400 ml with unfiltered water. Unfiltered noted on bottle. The unfiltered bottle (BWT) is only 50% filled due to the cap not being screwed on enough during transport to lab. All vials/bottles were individually wrapped and so the water did not contaminate other samples in the cooler. Apologies - we had a team of 5 doing the sampling (and it took 2 hours). Collection photo - difficult to get 1 m2 since the whole team is super short.

Additional_Sampling_Notes: Site was downstream of a boat launch. One boat passed by while sampling, 3 others launched then went upriver. Deviation: We accidentally proceeded from Phase 2 to Phase 5. We stored the labelled filter as specified but had to then use a new one to complete Phases 2 and 4. We did not save this filter. Our OCN vials also had septa, which we did not expect according to the protocol. We instead followed the protocols for vials with septa.

Weather: Partly cloudy, Overcast, Overcast for first half, then sunny with some clouds second 1/2
MiniDot_Notes: Sensor was tied to a rock on shore, and laid ontop of another bedrock chunk lying on the bank/shore. It was tied to a rope and allowed to settle in relatively shallow banks and in the flow.
Additional_Sampling_Notes: Ice chunks in the river mixed/floating along with small woody debris and some foam.  Lots of trash on the banks, some zebra mussel shells. Banks were limestone bedrock, weathered and big chunks, but area where samples were taken (right on shoreline) was sandy-silty-muddy substrate with few pebbles.

Sediment_Collection_Depth_cm: 1-3 cm as described in the protocol
Additional_Sampling_Notes: 90-95% of stream in area covered by snow. Labeled filter only used for 3 ICR samples, water in the needle froze after completing the 2nd replicate. Labeled filter preserved and new filter and needle used for rest of filtered samples. DO sensor placement, all water sampling, and some sediment sampling performed on depositional zone on the inside of a channel bend. Additional sediment gathered about 20 m downstream from the lip of a pool. Right before shipping (taking out of the refrigerator), frost was observed on ziploc bags and bulk water samples felt frozen in their bottles.
